ROCm decode: HIP graph capture for whole-token replay (resume after compact)

Status: NEXT. Picks up where 2026-05-09 session left off after blocking-sync fix made per-token CPU sync visible as the real remaining bottleneck.

Context (preserved across compaction)
- Decode baseline this branch: 15.35 t/s with blocking sync (DS4_ROCM_SCHEDULE_BLOCKING). Was 14.0 t/s pre-router-fusion. Prefill 39.5 t/s.
- Wall per token = ~65 ms. user CPU now ~3.6s / 33s wall (was 18s spinning).
- Production decode driver: metal_graph_eval_token_raw_swa_top at ds4.c:12201.
- Per-token kernel count: ~250 launches across 43 layers + output head + indexer topk + sampling.
- ds4_metal_end_commands at ds4_rocm.c:1433 calls hipDeviceSynchronize — one per token.

Goal
Capture the whole-token decode graph once during the first decoded token, then hipGraphLaunch + hipDeviceSynchronize per subsequent token. Eliminate per-kernel CPU launch overhead from the HIP runtime side.

Approach
1. Add a session-scoped HIP graph capture wrapper in ds4_rocm.c: ds4_metal_begin_capture / ds4_metal_end_capture. Use hipStreamBeginCapture(stream, hipStreamCaptureModeThreadLocal) on a dedicated stream + hipStreamEndCapture into a hipGraph_t, then hipGraphInstantiate.
2. Refactor ds4_metal_begin_commands / ds4_metal_end_commands to optionally route launches to the capture stream when capture is active. Currently launches go to default stream (NULL).
3. In ds4.c metal_graph_eval_token_raw_swa_top: on first decode token after a stable shape is reached, call begin_capture, replay the existing kernel sequence, end_capture, store hipGraphExec_t in the graph struct. On subsequent tokens, call hipGraphLaunch + readback + sync.
4. Constraints: pos changes per token (it is a kernel arg). HIP graphs support kparam updates via hipGraphExecKernelNodeSetParams, but that adds complexity. Alternative: pass pos via a small device-side scalar tensor that the host updates with hipMemcpyAsync before each replay. Pick the simpler path first.
5. Sampling readback (g->comp_selected, 4 bytes) stays the same — that is one tensor_read per token, unavoidable for greedy sampling.

Risks
- Graph capture rejects calls that allocate (rocm_upload_mapped happens for non-registered weights, but production weights ARE registered so the upload just returns the registered devptr — no allocation). Verify this before capturing.
- Per-token state changes other than pos: layer_raw_cache rotation, n_raw counter, comp state. Audit metal_graph_encode_token_raw_swa for any host-side branches that change graph topology between tokens.
- HIP graphs on gfx1151 had ~1.10x speedup at noop-level in prior testing (tsk-16 / tsk-20). Real decode might be larger because per-token sync overhead is visible now. Expected: 5-15% decode improvement.

